# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: key-rotation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] A **cryptoperiod** is the time span during which a specific cryptographic key is authorized for use.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] NIST's guidelines typically recommend a long-term cryptoperiod of 1 - 3 years for asymmetric keys and ≤ 2 years for symmetric keys.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] Factors to consider include the strength of the underlying encryption algorithm, key length, the likelihood of compromise through a security breach and the availability of mechanisms of revoking keys.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] In traditional cryptographic practice, keys were changed at regular intervals, typically at the same time each day.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] The code word for a key change, in NSA parlance, is **HJ** or **Hotel Juliet** in the NATO phonetic alphabet.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] When cryptographic devices began to be used in large scale, those who had to update the key had to set a specific time to synchronize the re-key.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] This was accomplished at the hour (H) the Julian (J) Date changed, among crypto-accountants, managers and users the jargon "HJ" became the accepted term meaning it was time to change the crypto-key.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] During the Vietnam War, the United States issued its forces a series of secure voice encryption equipment code-named NESTOR.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] Army history: "To maintain compatibility, key changes had to occur simultaneously in all units.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] The time chosen for this change was midnight, tactically the worst possible time because the greatest number of enemy contacts occurred from 2200 to 0200.
[src:key-rotation/cryptoperiod] Moreover, where several units shared the same keying device, having to move at night to change key settings was inconvenient and dangerous and added to the reasons for not using the equipment.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] For TLS, the long-term secret is typically the private key of the server.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy protects past sessions against future compromises of keys or passwords.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] By generating a unique session key for every session a user initiates, the compromise of a single session key will not affect any data other than that exchanged in the specific session protected by that particular key.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This by itself is not sufficient for forward secrecy, which additionally requires that a long-term secret compromise does not affect the security of past session keys.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy protects data on the transport layer of a network that uses common transport layer security protocols, including OpenSSL, when its long-term secret keys are compromised, as with the Heartbleed security bug.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] If forward secrecy is used, encrypted communications and sessions recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future, even if the adversary actively interfered, for example via a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The value of forward secrecy is that it protects past communication.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This reduces the motivation for attackers to compromise keys.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] For instance, if an attacker learns a long-term key, but the compromise is detected and the long-term key is revoked and updated, relatively little information is leaked in a forward secure system.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The value of forward secrecy depends on the assumed capabilities of an adversary.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy has value if an adversary is assumed to be able to obtain secret keys from a device (read access) but is either detected or unable to modify the way session keys are generated in the device (full compromise).
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In some cases an adversary who can read long-term keys from a device may also be able to modify the functioning of the session key generator, as in the backdoored Dual Elliptic Curve Deterministic Random Bit Generator.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] If an adversary can make the random number generator predictable, then past traffic will be protected but all future traffic will be compromised.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy typically uses an ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to prevent reading past traffic.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange is often signed by the server using a static signing key.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] If an adversary can steal (or obtain through a court order) this static (long term) signing key, the adversary can masquerade as the server to the client and as the client to the server and implement a classic man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The term "perfect forward secrecy" was coined by C.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Günther in 1990 and further discussed by Whitfield Diffie, Paul van Oorschot, and Michael James Wiener in 1992, where it was used to describe a property of the Station-to-Station protocol.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy has also been used to describe the analogous property of password-authenticated key agreement protocols where the long-term secret is a (shared) password.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In 2000 the IEEE first ratified IEEE 1363, which establishes the related one-party and two-party forward secrecy properties of various standard key agreement schemes.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] An encryption system has the property of forward secrecy if plain-text (decrypted) inspection of the data exchange that occurs during key agreement phase of session initiation does not reveal the key that was used to encrypt the remainder of the session.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Alice and Bob use a key exchange algorithm such as Diffie–Hellman, to securely agree on an ephemeral session key.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] They use the keys from step 1 only to authenticate one another during this process.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Alice sends Bob a message, encrypting it with a symmetric cipher using the session key negotiated in step 2.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Bob decrypts Alice's message using the key negotiated in step 2.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The process repeats for each new message sent, starting from step 2 (and switching Alice and Bob's roles as sender/receiver as appropriate).
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy (achieved by generating new session keys for each message) ensures that past communications cannot be decrypted if one of the keys generated in an iteration of step 2 is compromised, since such a key is only used to encrypt a single message.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy also ensures that past communications cannot be decrypted if the long-term private keys from step 1 are compromised.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] However, masquerading as Alice or Bob would be possible going forward if this occurred, possibly compromising all future messages.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy is designed to prevent the compromise of a long-term secret key from affecting the confidentiality of past conversations.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] However, forward secrecy cannot defend against a successful cryptanalysis of the underlying ciphers being used, since a cryptanalysis consists of finding a way to decrypt an encrypted message without the key, and forward secrecy only protects keys, not the ciphers themselves.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This would allow the recovery of old plaintexts even in a system employing forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Non-interactive forward-secure key exchange protocols face additional threats that are not relevant to interactive protocols.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Proactively retiring private keys on a schedule mitigates, but does not eliminate, this attack.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In a *malicious key exhaustion* attack, the attacker sends many messages to the recipient and exhausts the private key material, forcing a protocol to choose between failing closed (and enabling denial of service attacks) or failing open (and giving up some amount of forward secrecy).
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Most key exchange protocols are *interactive*, requiring bidirectional communication between the parties.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] A protocol that permits the sender to transmit data without first needing to receive any replies from the recipient may be called *non-interactive*, or *asynchronous*, or *zero round-trip time* (0-RTT).
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] These use cases have stimulated interest in non-interactive key exchange, and, as forward security is a desirable property in a key-exchange protocol, in non-interactive forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This combination has been identified as desirable since at least 1996.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] However, combining forward secrecy and non-interactivity has proven challenging; it had been suspected that forward secrecy with protection against replay attacks was impossible non-interactively, but it has been shown to be possible to achieve all three desiderata.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Broadly, two approaches to non-interactive forward secrecy have been explored, *pre-computed keys* and *puncturable encryption*.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] With pre-computed keys, many key pairs are created and the public keys shared, with the private keys destroyed after a message has been received using the corresponding public key.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This approach has been deployed as part of the Signal protocol.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In puncturable encryption, the recipient modifies their private key after receiving a message in such a way that the new private key cannot read the message but the public key is unchanged.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Green & Miers (2015) make use of hierarchical identity-based encryption and attribute-based encryption, while Günther et al.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] (2017) use a different construction that can be based on any hierarchical identity-based scheme.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] (2020) experimentally found that modifying QUIC to use a 0-RTT forward secure and replay-resistant key exchange implemented with puncturable encryption incurred significantly increased resource usage, but not so much as to make practical use infeasible.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Weak perfect forward secrecy (Wpfs) is the weaker property whereby when agents' long-term keys are compromised, the secrecy of previously established session keys is guaranteed, but only for sessions in which the adversary did not actively interfere.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This new notion, and the distinction between this and forward secrecy, was introduced by Hugo Krawczyk in 2005.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] This weaker definition implicitly requires that full (perfect) forward secrecy maintains the secrecy of previously established session keys even in sessions where the adversary *did* actively interfere or attempted to act as a man in the middle.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Forward secrecy is present in several protocol implementations, such as SSH and IPsec (RFC 2412), though it is optional in the latter.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Off-the-Record Messaging, a cryptography protocol and library for many instant messaging clients, as well as OMEMO which provides additional features such as multi-user functionality in such clients, both provide forward secrecy as well as deniable encryption.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In Transport Layer Security (TLS), cipher suites based on Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE-RSA, DHE-DSA) and elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE-RSA, ECDHE-ECDSA) are available.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In theory, TLS can use forward secrecy since SSLv3, but many implementations do not offer forward secrecy or provided it with lower-grade encryption.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] TLS 1.3 removed support for RSA for key exchange, leaving Diffie–Hellman (with forward secrecy) as the sole algorithm for key exchange.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] OpenSSL supports forward secrecy using elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman since version 1.0, with a computational overhead of approximately 15% for the initial handshake.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The Signal Protocol uses the Double Ratchet Algorithm to provide forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] On the other hand, among popular protocols currently in use, WPA Personal did not support forward secrecy before WPA3.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Since late 2011, Google provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, Google Docs service, and encrypted search services.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Since November 2013, Twitter provided forward secrecy with TLS to its users.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Wikis hosted by the Wikimedia Foundation have all provided forward secrecy to users since July 2014, and have required the use of forward secrecy since August 2018.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Facebook reported as part of an investigation into email encryption that, as of May 2014, 74% of hosts that support STARTTLS also provide forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] At WWDC 2016, Apple announced that all iOS apps would need to use App Transport Security (ATS), a feature which enforces the use of HTTPS transmission.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] Specifically, ATS requires the use of an encryption cipher that provides forward secrecy.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] ATS became mandatory for apps on January 1, 2017.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] The Signal messaging application employs forward secrecy in its protocol, notably differentiating it from messaging protocols based on PGP.
[src:key-rotation/forward-secrecy] In one survey in June 2025, forward secrecy was supported by about 95% of popular websites when accessed with modern browsers, while 0.2% did not support it at all.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A **key** in cryptography is a piece of information, usually a string of numbers or letters that are stored in a file, which, when processed through a cryptographic algorithm, can encode or decode cryptographic data.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Based on the used method, the key can be different sizes and varieties, but in all cases, the strength of the encryption relies on the security of the key being maintained.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A key's security strength is dependent on its algorithm, the size of the key, the generation of the key, and the process of key exchange.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The key is what is used to encrypt data from plaintext to ciphertext.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] There are different methods for utilizing keys and encryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Symmetric cryptography refers to the practice of the same key being used for both encryption and decryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Asymmetric cryptography has separate keys for encrypting and decrypting.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] These keys are known as the public and private keys, respectively.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Since the key protects the confidentiality and integrity of the system, it is important to be kept secret from unauthorized parties.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] With public key cryptography, only the private key must be kept secret, but with symmetric cryptography, it is important to maintain the confidentiality of the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Kerckhoff's principle states that the entire security of the cryptographic system relies on the secrecy of the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Key size is the number of bits in the key defined by the algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] This size defines the upper bound of the cryptographic algorithm's security.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The larger the key size, the longer it will take before the key is compromised by a brute force attack.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Since perfect secrecy is not feasible for key algorithms, researches are now more focused on computational security.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] In the past, keys were required to be a minimum of 40 bits in length, however, as technology advanced, these keys were being broken quicker and quicker.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] As a response, restrictions on symmetric keys were enhanced to be greater in size.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Currently, 2048 bit RSA is commonly used, which is sufficient for current systems.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] However, current RSA key sizes would all be cracked quickly with a powerful quantum computer.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] "The keys used in public key cryptography have some mathematical structure.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] For example, public keys used in the RSA system are the product of two prime numbers.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Thus public key systems require longer key lengths than symmetric systems for an equivalent level of security.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] To prevent a key from being guessed, keys need to be generated randomly and contain sufficient entropy.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The problem of how to safely generate random keys is difficult and has been addressed in many ways by various cryptographic systems.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A key can directly be generated by using the output of a Random Bit Generator (RBG), a system that generates a sequence of unpredictable and unbiased bits.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A RBG can be used to directly produce either a symmetric key or the random output for an asymmetric key pair generation.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Alternatively, a key can also be indirectly created during a key-agreement transaction, from another key or from a password.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Some operating systems include tools for "collecting" entropy from the timing of unpredictable operations such as disk drive head movements.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] For the production of small amounts of keying material, ordinary dice provide a good source of high-quality randomness.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The security of a key is dependent on how a key is exchanged between parties.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Establishing a secured communication channel is necessary so that outsiders cannot obtain the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A key establishment scheme (or key exchange) is used to transfer an encryption key among entities.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Key agreement and key transport are the two types of a key exchange scheme that are used to be remotely exchanged between entities .
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] In a key agreement scheme, a secret key, which is used between the sender and the receiver to encrypt and decrypt information, is set up to be sent indirectly.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] All parties exchange information (the shared secret) that permits each party to derive the secret key material.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] In a key transport scheme, encrypted keying material that is chosen by the sender is transported to the receiver.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Either symmetric key or asymmetric key techniques can be used in both schemes.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange and Rivest-Shamir-Adleman (RSA) are the most two widely used key exchange algorithms.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman constructed the Diffie–Hellman algorithm, which was the first public key algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange protocol allows key exchange over an insecure channel by electronically generating a shared key between two parties.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] On the other hand, RSA is a form of the asymmetric key system which consists of three steps: key generation, encryption, and decryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Key confirmation delivers an assurance between the key confirmation recipient and provider that the shared keying materials are correct and established.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends key confirmation to be integrated into a key establishment scheme to validate its implementations.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Key management concerns the generation, establishment, storage, usage and replacement of cryptographic keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A key management system (KMS) typically includes three steps of establishing, storing and using keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] The base of security for the generation, storage, distribution, use and destruction of keys depends on successful key management protocols.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A password is a memorized series of characters including letters, digits, and other special symbols that are used to verify identity.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] It is often produced by a human user or a password management software to protect personal and sensitive information or generate cryptographic keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Passwords are often created to be memorized by users and may contain non-random information such as dictionary words.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] On the other hand, a key can help strengthen password protection by implementing a cryptographic algorithm which is difficult to guess or replace the password altogether.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A key is generated based on random or pseudo-random data and can often be unreadable to humans.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] A password is less safe than a cryptographic key due to its low entropy, randomness, and human-readable properties.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] However, the password may be the only secret data that is accessible to the cryptographic algorithm for information security in some applications such as securing information in storage devices.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Thus, a deterministic algorithm called a key derivation function (KDF) uses a password to generate the secure cryptographic keying material to compensate for the password's weakness.
[src:key-rotation/key-cryptography] Various methods such as adding a salt or key stretching may be used in the generation.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] This Key Management Cheat Sheet provides developers with guidance for implementation of cryptographic key management within an application in a secure manner.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Formulate a plan for the overall organization's cryptographic strategy to guide developers working on different applications and ensure that each application's cryptographic capability meets minimum requirements and best practices.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identify the cryptographic and key management requirements for your application and map all components that process or store cryptographic key material.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Selection of the cryptographic and key management algorithms to use within a given application should begin with an understanding of the objectives of the application.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, if the application is required to store data securely, then the developer should select an algorithm suite that supports the objective of data at rest protection security.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Applications that are required to transmit and receive data would select an algorithm suite that supports the objective of data in transit protection.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] We have provided recommendations on the selection of crypto suites within an application based on application and security objectives.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Application developers oftentimes begin the development of crypto and key management capabilities by examining what is available in a library.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] However, an analysis of the real needs of the application should be conducted to determine the optimal key management approach.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Begin by understanding the security objectives of the application which will then drive the selection of cryptographic protocols that are best suited.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys to create the data encryption keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Once the understanding of the security needs of the application is achieved, developers can determine what protocols and algorithms are required.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Once the protocols and algorithms are understood, you can begin to define the different types of keys that will support the application's objectives.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] **Authentication of End Devices:** Pre-shared symmetric keys, Trusted certificates, Trust Anchors.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] **Integrity Protection:** Message Authentication Codes (MACs).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to `NIST SP 800-57 Part 1`, many algorithms and schemes that provide a security service use a hash function as a component of the algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hash functions can be found in digital signature algorithms (`FIPS186`), Keyed-Hash Message Authentication Codes (HMAC) (`FIPS198`), key-derivation functions/methods (`NIST Special Publications (SP) 800-56A, 800-56B, 800-56C and 800-108`), and random number generators (`NIST SP 800-90A`).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Approved hash functions are defined in `FIPS180`.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] `NIST SP 800-57 Part 1` recognizes three basic classes of approved cryptographic algorithms: hash functions, symmetric- key algorithms and asymmetric-key algorithms.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The classes are defined by the number of cryptographic keys that are used in conjunction with the algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The NSA released a report, Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite 2.0 which lists the cryptographic algorithms that are expected to be remain strong even with advances in quantum computing.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Cryptographic hash functions do not require keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hash functions generate a relatively small digest (hash value) from a (possibly) large input in a way that is fundamentally difficult to reverse (i.e., it is hard to find an input that will produce a given output).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To compress messages for digital signature generation and verification (Section 4.2.4).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To derive keys in key-establishment algorithms (Section 4.2.5).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To generate deterministic random numbers (Section 4.2.7).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric-key algorithms (sometimes known as secret-key algorithms) transform data in a way that is fundamentally difficult to undo without knowledge of a secret key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The key is "symmetric" because the same key is used for a cryptographic operation and its inverse (e.g., encryption and decryption).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric keys are often known by more than one entity; however, the key shall not be disclosed to entities that are not authorized access to the data protected by that algorithm and key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To provide authentication and integrity services (Section 4.2.3) in the form of Message Authentication Codes (MACs); the same key is used to generate the MAC and to validate it.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] MACs normally employ either a symmetric key-encryption algorithm or a cryptographic hash function as their cryptographic primitive.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] As part of the key-establishment process (Section 4.2.5).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Asymmetric-key algorithms, commonly known as public-key algorithms, use two related keys (i.e., a key pair) to perform their functions: a public key and a private key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The public key may be known by anyone; the private key should be under the sole control of the entity that "owns" the key pair.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Even though the public and private keys of a key pair are related, knowledge of the public key does not reveal the private key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To establish cryptographic keying material (Section 4.2.5).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] To generate random numbers (Section 4.2.7).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Message Authentication Codes (MACs) provide data authentication and integrity.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A MAC is a cryptographic checksum on the data that is used in order to provide assurance that the data has not changed and that the MAC was computed by the expected entity.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Although message integrity is often provided using non-cryptographic techniques known as error detection codes, these codes can be altered by an adversary to effect an action to the adversary's benefit.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The use of an approved cryptographic mechanism, such as a MAC, can alleviate this problem.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] In addition, the MAC can provide a recipient with assurance that the originator of the data is a key holder (i.e., an entity authorized to have the key).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] MACs are often used to authenticate the originator to the recipient when only those two parties share the MAC key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Digital signatures are used to provide authentication, integrity and non-repudiation.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Digital signatures are used in conjunction with hash functions and are computed on data of any length (up to a limit that is determined by the hash function).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] `FIPS186` specifies algorithms that are approved for the computation of digital signatures.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Symmetric key-wrapping keys are used to encrypt other keys using symmetric-key algorithms.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Key-wrapping keys are also known as key encrypting keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Review `NIST SP 800-57` (Recommendation for Key Management) for recommended guidelines on key strength for specific algorithm implementations.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] When encrypting keys for storage or distribution, always encrypt a cryptographic key with another key of equal or greater cryptographic strength.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] When moving to Elliptic Curve-based algorithms, choose a key length that meets or exceeds the comparative strength of other algorithms in use within your system.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Formulate a strategy for the overall organization's cryptographic strategy to guide developers working on different applications and ensure that each application's cryptographic capability meets minimum requirements and best practices.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys stored in memory for a long time can become "burned in".
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] This can be mitigated by splitting the key into components that are frequently updated.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Loss or corruption of the memory media on which keys and/or certificates are stored, and recovery planning, according to `NIST SP 800-57`.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Plan for the recovery from possible corruption of the memory media necessary for key or certificate generation, registration, and/or distribution systems, subsystems, or components as recommended in `NIST SP 800-57`.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ephemeral keys can provide perfect forward secrecy protection, which means a compromise of the server's long term signing key does not compromise the confidentiality of past sessions.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to NIST, in general, a single key should be used for only one purpose (e.g., encryption, authentication, key wrapping, random number generation, or digital signatures).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Limiting the use of a key limits the damage that could be done if the key is compromised.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Some uses of keys interfere with each other.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, the length of time the key may be required for each use and purpose.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Retention requirements of the data may differ for different data types.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] According to `NIST SP 800-133`, cryptographic modules are the set of hardware, software, and/or firmware that implements security functions (including cryptographic algorithms and key generation) and is contained within a cryptographic module boundary to provide protection of the keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Cryptographic keys shall be generated within cryptographic module with at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliance.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For explanatory purposes, consider the cryptographic module in which a key is generated to be the key-generating module.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Any random value required by the key-generating module shall be generated within that module; that is, the Random Bit Generator that generates the random value shall be implemented within cryptographic module with at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliance that generates the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Hardware cryptographic modules are preferred over software cryptographic modules for protection.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The generated keys shall be transported (when necessary) using secure channels and shall be used by their associated cryptographic algorithm within at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` compliant cryptographic modules.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For additional detail for the recommendations in this section refer to `NIST Special Paper 800-133`.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys must be protected on both volatile and persistent memory, ideally processed within secure cryptographic modules.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Keys should never be stored in plaintext format.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure all keys are stored in a cryptographic vault, such as a hardware security module (HSM) or isolated cryptographic service.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] If you are planning on storing keys in offline devices/databases, then encrypt the keys using Key Encryption Keys (KEKs) prior to the export of the key material.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] KEK length (and algorithm) should be equivalent to or greater in strength than the keys being protected.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that keys have integrity protections applied while in storage (consider dual purpose algorithms that support encryption and Message Code Authentication (MAC)).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that standard application level code never reads or uses cryptographic keys in any way and use key management libraries.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Ensure that keys and cryptographic operation is done inside the sealed vault.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] All work should be done in the vault (such as key access, encryption, decryption, signing, etc).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For a more complete guide to storing sensitive information such as keys, see the Secrets Management Cheat Sheet.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Data that has been encrypted with lost cryptographic keys will never be recovered.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Therefore, it is essential that the application incorporate a secure key backup capability, especially for applications that support data at rest encryption for long-term data stores.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] When backing up keys, ensure that the database that is used to store the keys is encrypted using at least a `FIPS 140-2 or 140-3` validated module.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] It is sometimes useful to escrow key material for use in investigations and for re-provisioning of key material to users in the event that the key is lost or corrupted.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Never escrow keys used for performing digital signatures, but consider the need to escrow keys that support encryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Oftentimes, escrow can be performed by the Certificate Authority (CA) or key management system that provisions certificates and keys, however in some instances separate APIs must be implemented to allow the system to perform the escrow for the application.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Accountability involves the identification of those that have access to, or control of, cryptographic keys throughout their lifecycles.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Accountability can be an effective tool to help prevent key compromises and to reduce the impact of compromises once they are detected.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Although it is preferred that no humans are able to view keys, as a minimum, the key management system should account for all individuals who are able to view plaintext cryptographic keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] In addition, more sophisticated key-management systems may account for all individuals authorized to access or control any cryptographic keys, whether in plaintext or ciphertext form.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] It tends to protect against compromise, because individuals with access to the key know that their access to the key is known.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] It is very useful in recovering from a detected key compromise to know where the key was used and what data or other keys were protected by the compromised key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Certain principles have been found to be useful in enforcing the accountability of cryptographic keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] These principles might not apply to all systems or all types of keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying the dates and times of key use, along with the data that is protected.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying other keys that are protected by a symmetric or private key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The protective mechanisms employed should be periodically reassessed with respect to the level of security that they provide and are expected to provide in the future, and that the mechanisms correctly and effectively support the appropriate policies.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] New technology developments and attacks should be taken into consideration.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] On a more frequent basis, the actions of the humans that use, operate and maintain the system should be reviewed to verify that the humans continue to follow established security procedures.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Strong cryptographic systems can be compromised by lax and inappropriate human actions.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Highly unusual events should be noted and reviewed as possible indicators of attempted attacks on the system.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of the integrity of a key means that the key is incorrect - either that the key has been modified (either deliberately or accidentally), or that another key has been substituted; this includes a deletion (non-availability) of the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The substitution or modification of a key used to provide integrity calls into question the integrity of all information protected by the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] This information could have been provided by, or changed by, an unauthorized entity that knows the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The substitution of a public or secret key that will be used (at a later time) to encrypt data could allow an unauthorized entity (who knows the decryption key) to decrypt data that was encrypted using the encryption key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's usage or application association means that the key could be used for the wrong purpose (e.g., for key establishment instead of digital signatures) or for the wrong application, and could result in the compromise of information protected by the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's association with the owner or other entity means that the identity of the other entity cannot be assured (i.e., one does not know who the other entity really is) or that information cannot be processed correctly (e.g., decrypted with the correct key).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise of a key's association with other information means that there is no association at all, or the association is with the wrong "information".
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] This could cause the cryptographic services to fail, information to be lost, or the security of the information to be compromised.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Certain protective measures may be taken in order to minimize the likelihood or consequences of a key compromise.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Similar affect as ransomware, except that you can't pay the ransom and get the key back.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Preventing humans from viewing plaintext symmetric and private keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Restricting plaintext symmetric and private keys to physically protected containers.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] This includes key generators, key-transport devices, key loaders, cryptographic modules, and key-storage devices.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Using integrity checks to ensure that the integrity of a key or its association with other data has not been compromised.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] For example, keys may be wrapped (i.e., encrypted) in such a manner that unauthorized modifications to the wrapping or to the associations will be detected.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Employing key confirmation (see NIST SP 800-57 Part 1 Section 4.2.5.5) to help ensure that the proper key was, in fact, established.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Establishing an accountability system that keeps track of each access to symmetric and private keys in plaintext form.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Providing a cryptographic integrity check on the key (e.g., using a MAC or a digital signature).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The use of trusted timestamps for signed data. i.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Destroying keys as soon as they are no longer needed.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Creating a compromise-recovery plan, especially in the case of a CA compromise.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise-recovery plan is essential for restoring cryptographic security services in the event of a key compromise.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] A compromise-recovery plan shall be documented and easily accessible.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The identification and contact info of the personnel to perform the recovery actions.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] An inventory of all cryptographic keys and their use (e.g., the location of all certificates in a system).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The education of all appropriate personnel on the recovery procedures.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] An identification and contact info of all personnel needed to support the recovery procedures.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Policies that key-revocation checking be enforced (to minimize the effect of a compromise).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] The monitoring of the re-keying operations (to ensure that all required operations are performed for all affected keys).
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identification of all information that may be compromised as a result of the incident.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Identification of all signatures that may be invalid, due to the compromise of a signing key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Distribution of new keying material, if required.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Implement integrity controls on objects stored in the trust store.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Do not allow for export of keys held within the trust store without authentication and authorization.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Setup strict policies and procedures for exporting key material from applications to network applications and other components.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Implement a secure process for updating the trust store.
[src:key-rotation/key-management-cheat-sheet] Use only reputable crypto libraries that are well maintained and updated, as well as tested and validated by third-party organizations (e.g., `NIST`/`FIPS`).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:key-rotation/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] In cryptography, **key size** or **key length** refers to the number of bits in a key used by a cryptographic algorithm (such as a cipher).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Key length defines the upper-bound on an algorithm's security (i.e. a logarithmic measure of the fastest known attack against an algorithm), because the security of all algorithms can be violated by brute-force attacks.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Ideally, the lower-bound on an algorithm's security is by design equal to the key length (that is, the algorithm's design does not detract from the degree of security inherent in the key length).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Most symmetric-key algorithms are designed to have security equal to their key length.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] However, after design, a new attack might be discovered.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] For instance, Triple DES was designed to have a 168-bit key, but an attack of complexity 2112 is now known (i.e.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Triple DES now only has 112 bits of security, and of the 168 bits in the key the attack has rendered 56 'ineffective' towards security).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Nevertheless, as long as the security (understood as "the amount of effort it would take to gain access") is sufficient for a particular application, then it does not matter if key length and security coincide.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] This is important for asymmetric-key algorithms, because no such algorithm is known to satisfy this property; elliptic curve cryptography comes the closest with an effective security of roughly half its key length.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Keys are used to control the operation of a cipher so that only the correct key can convert encrypted text (ciphertext) to plaintext.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The widely accepted notion that the security of the system should depend on the key alone has been explicitly formulated by Auguste Kerckhoffs (in the 1880s) and Claude Shannon (in the 1940s); the statements are known as Kerckhoffs' principle and Shannon's Maxim respectively.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] A key should, therefore, be large enough that a brute-force attack (possible against any encryption algorithm) is infeasible – i.e. would take too long and/or would take too much memory to execute.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Shannon's work on information theory showed that to achieve so-called 'perfect secrecy', the key length must be at least as large as the message and only used once (this algorithm is called the one-time pad).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Encryption systems are often grouped into families.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Common families include symmetric systems (e.g.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] RSA and Elliptic-curve cryptography [ECC]).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] They may be grouped according to the central algorithm used (e.g.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Because each of these has a different level of cryptographic complexity, it is usual to have different key sizes for the same level of security, depending upon the algorithm used.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] For example, the security available with a 1024-bit key using asymmetric RSA is considered approximately equal in security to an 80-bit key in a symmetric algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The actual degree of security achieved over time varies, as more computational power and more powerful mathematical analytic methods become available.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] For this reason, cryptologists tend to look at indicators that an algorithm or key length shows signs of potential vulnerability, to move to longer key sizes or more difficult algorithms.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] For example, as of May 2007, a 1039-bit integer was factored with the special number field sieve using 400 computers over 11 months.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The factored number was of a special form; the special number field sieve cannot be used on RSA keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The computation is roughly equivalent to breaking a 700 bit RSA key.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] However, this might be an advance warning that 1024 bit RSA keys used in secure online commerce should be deprecated, since they may become breakable in the foreseeable future.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The 2015 Logjam attack revealed additional dangers in using Diffie-Hellman key exchange when only one or a few common 1024-bit or smaller prime moduli are in use.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] This practice, somewhat common at the time, allows large amounts of communications to be compromised at the expense of attacking a small number of primes.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Even if a symmetric cipher is currently unbreakable by exploiting structural weaknesses in its algorithm, it may be possible to run through the entire space of keys in what is known as a brute-force attack.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Because longer symmetric keys require exponentially more work to brute force search, a sufficiently long symmetric key makes this line of attack impractical.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] With a key of length *n* bits, there are 2n possible keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] This number grows very rapidly as *n* increases.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The large number of operations (2128) required to try all possible 128-bit keys is widely considered out of reach for conventional digital computing techniques for the foreseeable future.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] However, a quantum computer capable of running Grover's algorithm would be able to search the possible keys more efficiently.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] If a suitably sized quantum computer would reduce a 128-bit key down to 64-bit security, roughly a DES equivalent.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] This is one of the reasons why AES supports key lengths of 256 bits and longer.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] IBM's Lucifer cipher was selected in 1974 as the base for what would become the Data Encryption Standard.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Lucifer's key length was reduced from 128 bits to 56 bits, which the NSA and NIST argued was sufficient for non-governmental protection at the time.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The NSA has major computing resources and a large budget; some cryptographers including Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman complained that this made the cipher so weak that NSA computers would be able to break a DES key in a day through brute force parallel computing.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The NSA disputed this, claiming that brute-forcing DES would take them "something like 91 years".
[src:key-rotation/key-size] However, by the late 90s, it became clear that DES could be cracked in a few days' time-frame with custom-built hardware such as could be purchased by a large corporation or government.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The book *Cracking DES* (O'Reilly and Associates) tells of the successful ability in 1998 to break 56-bit DES by a brute-force attack mounted by a cyber civil rights group with limited resources; see EFF DES cracker.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Even before that demonstration, 56 bits was considered insufficient length for symmetric algorithm keys for general use.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Because of this, DES was replaced in most security applications by Triple DES, which has 112 bits of security when using 168-bit keys (triple key).
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The Advanced Encryption Standard published in 2001 uses key sizes of 128, 192 or 256 bits.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Many observers consider 128 bits sufficient for the foreseeable future for symmetric algorithms of AES's quality until quantum computers become available.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] National Security Agency has issued guidance that it plans to switch to quantum computing resistant algorithms and now requires 256-bit AES keys for data classified up to Top Secret.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] National Institute for Standards and Technology, NIST proposed phasing out 80-bit keys by 2015.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] At 2005, 80-bit keys were allowed only until 2010.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Since 2015, NIST guidance says that "the use of keys that provide less than 112 bits of security strength for key agreement is now disallowed." NIST approved symmetric encryption algorithms include three-key Triple DES, and AES.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Approvals for two-key Triple DES and Skipjack were withdrawn in 2015; the NSA's Skipjack algorithm used in its Fortezza program employs 80-bit keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The effectiveness of public key cryptosystems depends on the intractability (computational and theoretical) of certain mathematical problems such as integer factorization.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] These problems are time-consuming to solve, but usually faster than trying all possible keys by brute force.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Thus, asymmetric keys must be longer for equivalent resistance to attack than symmetric algorithm keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The most common methods are assumed to be weak against sufficiently powerful quantum computers in the future.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Since 2015, NIST recommends a minimum of 2048-bit keys for RSA, an update to the widely accepted recommendation of a 1024-bit minimum since at least 2002.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] 1024-bit RSA keys are equivalent in strength to 80-bit symmetric keys, 2048-bit RSA keys to 112-bit symmetric keys, 3072-bit RSA keys to 128-bit symmetric keys, and 15360-bit RSA keys to 256-bit symmetric keys.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] In 2003, RSA Security claimed that 1024-bit keys were likely to become crackable sometime between 2006 and 2010, while 2048-bit keys are sufficient until 2030.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] As of 2020 the largest RSA key publicly known to be cracked is RSA-250 with 829 bits.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The Finite Field Diffie-Hellman algorithm has roughly the same key strength as RSA for the same key sizes.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The work factor for breaking Diffie-Hellman is based on the discrete logarithm problem, which is related to the integer factorization problem on which RSA's strength is based.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Thus, a 2048-bit Diffie-Hellman key has about the same strength as a 2048-bit RSA key.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Elliptic-curve cryptography (ECC) is an alternative set of asymmetric algorithms that is equivalently secure with shorter keys, requiring only approximately twice the bits as the equivalent symmetric algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] A 256-bit Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman (ECDH) key has approximately the same safety factor as a 128-bit AES key.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] A message encrypted with an elliptic key algorithm using a 109-bit long key was broken in 2004.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The NSA previously recommended 256-bit ECC for protecting classified information up to the SECRET level, and 384-bit for TOP SECRET; In 2015 it announced plans to transition to quantum-resistant algorithms by 2024, and until then recommends 384-bit for all classified information.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The two best known quantum computing attacks are based on Shor's algorithm and Grover's algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Of the two, Shor's offers the greater risk to current security systems.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Derivatives of Shor's algorithm are widely conjectured to be effective against all mainstream public-key algorithms including RSA, Diffie-Hellman and elliptic curve cryptography.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] According to Professor Gilles Brassard, an expert in quantum computing: "The time needed to factor an RSA integer is the same order as the time needed to use that same integer as modulus for a single RSA encryption.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] The implication of this attack is that all data encrypted using current standards based security systems such as the ubiquitous SSL used to protect e-commerce and Internet banking and SSH used to protect access to sensitive computing systems is at risk.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Encrypted data protected using public-key algorithms can be archived and may be broken at a later time, commonly known as retroactive/retrospective decryption or "harvest now, decrypt later".
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Mainstream symmetric ciphers (such as AES or Twofish) and collision resistant hash functions (such as SHA) are widely conjectured to offer greater security against known quantum computing attacks.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] They are widely thought most vulnerable to Grover's algorithm.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Bennett, Bernstein, Brassard, and Vazirani proved in 1996 that a brute-force key search on a quantum computer cannot be faster than roughly 2*n*/2 invocations of the underlying cryptographic algorithm, compared with roughly 2*n* in the classical case.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Thus in the presence of large quantum computers an *n*-bit key can provide at least *n*/2 bits of security.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] Quantum brute force is easily defeated by doubling the key length, which has little extra computational cost in ordinary use.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] This implies that at least a 256-bit symmetric key is required to achieve 128-bit security rating against a quantum computer.
[src:key-rotation/key-size] As mentioned above, the NSA announced in 2015 that it plans to transition to quantum-resistant algorithms.
